'''Désiré Nonka-Maho Doué''' ({{IPA|fr|deziʁe dwe, -due}}; born 3 June 2005) is a French professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as an [[attacking midfielder]] or [[Winger (association football)|winger]] for {{French football updater|PSG}} club [[Paris Saint-Germain FC|Paris Saint-Germain]] and the [[France national football team|France national team]]. Known for his pace, agility, passing, and flair, he is considered to be one of the best young players in the world.<ref name=":0" /><ref name=":1" /><ref name=":2" /><ref name=":3" />

Doué started his career at [[Stade Rennais FC|Rennes]], spending two seasons in Ligue 1. In 2024, he joined reigning French champions PSG in a transfer worth €50 million. In his [[2024–25 Paris Saint-Germain FC season|debut season]] for PSG, Doué was a prominent player as the club attained a [[Treble (association football)#Continental trebles|continental treble]], including their first-ever [[2025 UEFA Champions League final|UEFA Champions League]] title. His performances also earned him the [[Ligue 1 Young Player of the Year]] award, the [[2024–25 UEFA Champions League|Champions League's Young Player of the Season]], and the [[Golden Boy (award)|Golden Boy]]. The [[2025–26 Paris Saint-Germain FC season|following season]], he helped PSG win the [[2025–26 Ligue 1|Ligue 1]] and [[2026 UEFA Champions League final|UEFA Champions League]] for a second time in a row, earning the Ligue 1 Young Player of the Year award for the second consecutive season.

Doué is a former [[France national youth football team|France youth international]], representing his country at various youth levels and the [[France Olympic football team|Olympic team]] in [[Football at the 2024 Summer Olympics – Men's tournament|2024]], where he won a silver medal. He made his senior debut for France in March 2025.

==Club career==
===Rennes===
Doué began playing football with the youth academy of [[Stade Rennais FC|Rennes]] at the age of five in 2011. He began his senior career with their [[Reserve team|reserves]] in 2021, and started training with the senior side in February 2021.<ref name="auto">{{Cite web|url=https://www.footmercato.net/a8278659965667783859-rennes-desire-doue-signe-son-premier-contrat-professionnel|title=Rennes : Désiré Doué signe son premier contrat professionnel|website=Foot Mercato : Info Transferts Football - Actu Foot Transfert|date=15 April 2022 }}</ref> On 14 April 2022, he signed his first professional contract until 2024.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.lequipe.fr/Football/Actualites/Premier-contrat-pro-en-vue-a-rennes-pour-desire-doue/1312060|title=Premier contrat pro en vue à Rennes pour Désiré Doué |website=L'Équipe}}</ref>

On 7 August 2022, Doué made his professional debut for Rennes as a substitute in a 1–0 [[Ligue 1]] defeat at home to [[FC Lorient|Lorient]].<ref>{{Cite web |date=7 August 2022 |title=Rennes vs. Lorient |url=https://int.soccerway.com/matches/2022/08/07/france/ligue-1/stade-rennais-fc/football-cub-lorient-bretagne-sud/3802141/ |access-date=7 October 2022 |website=Soccerway}}</ref> On 31 August, he scored his first professional goal in a 3–1 league win at home over [[Stade Brestois 29|Brest]], becoming the first player born in 2005 to score in any of the major five European leagues.<ref>{{Cite web |date=31 August 2022 |title=Rennes vs. Brest |url=https://int.soccerway.com/matches/2022/08/31/france/ligue-1/stade-rennais-fc/stade-brestois-29/3802188/ |access-date=7 October 2022 |website=Soccerway}}</ref> On 6 October, Doué scored an 89th-minute winning goal for Rennes in a 2–1 [[UEFA Europa League]] home victory over [[FC Dynamo Kyiv|Dynamo Kyiv]], his first European goal.<ref>{{Cite web |date=6 October 2022 |title=Rennes vs. Dinamo Kiev |url=https://int.soccerway.com/matches/2022/10/06/europe/uefa-cup/stade-rennais-fc/fc-dynamo-kyiv/3946949/ |access-date=7 October 2022 |website=Soccerway}}</ref> The goal made him the youngest ever French scorer in European club competitions at 17 years, four months and four days of age.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Telford |first=S |date=12 October 2023 |title=Room for Doué? Guéla and Désiré both now starring for Rennes |url=https://www.ligue1.com/Articles/News/2023/10/12/room-for-doue-guela-and-desire-both-now-starring-for-rennes |website=Ligue 1 Uber Eats}}</ref> On 9 October, Doué scored a half-volley in the [[Derby Breton]] against [[FC Nantes|Nantes]], sealing a 3–0 win less than 60 seconds after coming on as a substitute in the 83rd minute.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Scahill |first=Liam |date=18 October 2022 |title=Désire Doué Is Displaying Preternatural Footballing Development At Stade Rennais |url=https://breakingthelines.com/player-analysis/desire-doue-is-displaying-preternatural-footballing-development-at-stade-rennais/ |website=Breaking The Lines}}</ref> On 2 November, Doué extended this contract with Rennes for another year until 2025.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Jucobin |first=Raphaël |date=2 November 2022 |title=OFFICIAL {{!}} DÉSIRÉ DOUÉ RENEWS RENNES CONTRACT TO 2025 |url=https://www.getfootballnewsfrance.com/2022/official-desire-doue-renews-rennes-contract-to-2025/ |website=Get French Football News}}</ref>

[[File:Lens - Stade Rennais (20-08-2023) 42.jpg|thumb|upright|left|Doué with [[Stade Rennais F.C.|Rennes]] in 2023]]
On 9 April 2023, Doué found himself substituted out in the final minutes of the 3–1 defeat against [[Olympique Lyonnais|Lyon]] after being introduced from the bench 18 minutes earlier. Rennes manager [[Bruno Génésio]] was critical of the midfielder in his post-match comments, but also gave him encouragement: "It does not mean I don’t have great trust in him and that he’ll fail to make a great career, but some things need to be understood faster".<ref>{{Cite web |last=Cheval |first=Bastien |date=9 April 2023 |title=RENNES' BRUNO GENESIO SUBSTITUTED DÉSIRÉ DOUÉ 18 MINUTES AFTER HIS INTRODUCTION AGAINST LYON |url=https://www.getfootballnewsfrance.com/2023/rennes-bruno-genesio-substituted-desire-doue-18-minutes-after-his-introduction-against-lyon/ |website=Get French Football News}}</ref> Doué finished the 2022–23 season in Ligue 1 with 29 appearances, 11 of which as a starter.

On 1 October 2023, Doué scored his first goal in the [[2023–24 Ligue 1]] season in a 3–1 win against Nantes.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Rauzy |first=François |date=1 October 2023 |title=Ligue 1 : le Stade Rennais s'impose dans le derby face à Nantes et reste invaincu cette saison |url=https://www.francebleu.fr/sports/football/en-direct-suivez-le-derby-stade-rennais-fc-nantes-avec-france-bleu-armorique-1002026 |website=France Bleu}}</ref> On 26 January 2024 against Lyon, he assisted Rennes' first goal by [[Martin Terrier]], and scored the second in a 3–2 win, playing as a left winger.<ref>{{Cite web |date=26 January 2024 |title=Two-goal Terrier runs Lyon ragged as Rennes wins French league thriller |url=https://apnews.com/article/rennes-lyon-ligue-1-2e99fd2d6a58e6ccc16d8bdb3d6b4234 |access-date=23 March 2024 |website=AP News}}</ref>

===Paris Saint-Germain===
On 17 August 2024, Doué joined fellow Ligue 1 club [[Paris Saint-Germain FC|Paris Saint-Germain]] in a transfer worth €50 million, not including bonuses.<ref>{{cite web |date=17 August 2024 |title=Désiré Doué is a Parisian! |url=https://en.psg.fr/teams/first-team/content/desire-doue-is-a-parisian-psg-paris-saint-germain-news-mercato-2425-2024-2025 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20241014001748/https://en.psg.fr/teams/first-team/content/desire-doue-is-a-parisian-psg-paris-saint-germain-news-mercato-2425-2024-2025 |archive-date=14 October 2024 |access-date=17 August 2024 |publisher=Paris Saint-Germain FC}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=Mercato : Désiré Doué officiellement transféré au Paris Saint-Germain (Transferts) |url=https://www.lequipe.fr/Football/Actualites/Mercato-desire-doue-officiellement-transfere-au-paris-saint-germain/1501890 |access-date=17 August 2024 |publisher=L'Équipe |language=fr}}</ref> He signed a contract valid until 30 June 2029.<ref>{{Cite web |date=17 August 2024 |title=PSG complete €50m deal for Désiré Doué, 19 |url=https://www.espn.co.uk/football/story/_/id/40891671/psg-complete-transfer-rennes-starlet-desire-doue |access-date=19 August 2024 |website=ESPN}}</ref> In doing so, he rejected an offer from German club [[FC Bayern Munich|Bayern Munich]].<ref>{{cite news |date=11 August 2024 |title=Désiré Doué chooses PSG over Bayern Munich |website=Get French Football News |url=https://www.getfootballnewsfrance.com/2024/desire-doue-chooses-psg-over-bayern-munich/ |access-date=19 August 2024}}</ref>

====2024–25: Young Player of the Season and European champion====
On 23 August, Doué made his debut for the reigning French champions as a substitute in a 6–0 win over [[Montpellier HSC|Montpellier]], wearing the number 14 shirt.<ref>{{cite web |date=23 August 2024 |title=Debut for Désiré Doué |url=https://en.psg.fr/teams/first-team/content/debut-for-desire-doue-paris-saint-germain-montpellier-herault-sc-ligue-1-2024-2025 |publisher=Paris Saint-Germain FC}}</ref> In the post-match interview, Doué stated that he didn't regret his decision to sign for PSG instead of Bayern.<ref>{{cite web |last=Eduardo |date=23 August 2024 |title=Doué Stands By PSG Choice Despite Bayern, Spurs Summer Interest |url=https://psgtalk.com/2024/08/doue-stands-psg-choice-despite-bayern-spurs-summer-interest/ |access-date=26 August 2024 |website=PSG Talk}}</ref> In the next match on 1 September, he recorded his first assist for PSG, a cross for a [[Randal Kolo Muani]] header to seal a 3–1 victory over [[Lille OSC|Lille]].<ref>{{cite web |date=1 September 2024 |title=PSG scrapes victory to reclaim top spot after Lille showdown |url=https://psgpost.com/posts/psg-scrapes-victory-to-reclaim-top-spot-after-lille-showdown-01j6qq3ndf04 |access-date=7 September 2024 |website=PSG Post}}</ref> On 18 September, Doué made his [[UEFA Champions League]] debut at the Parc des Princes against Spanish side [[Girona FC|Girona]].<ref>{{cite web |date=19 September 2024 |title=Willian Pacho, Desire Doue make Champions League debut in PSG's victory over Girona |url=https://psgpost.com/posts/willian-pacho-desire-doue-champions-league-debut-psg-victory-girona |access-date=11 December 2024 |website=PSG Post}}</ref> On 10 December, he scored his first Champions League goal in a 3–0 away win over [[FC Red Bull Salzburg|Red Bull Salzburg]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.footboom1.com/en/news/football/2165351-desire-doue-shines-in-psg-s-champions-league-victory |title=Désiré Doué Shines in PSG's Champions League Victory |website=FootBoom |date=11 December 2024 }}</ref> On 15 December, he was given his first man of the match award in Ligue 1 as a PSG player for his performance in a 3–1 home win against [[Olympique Lyonnais|Lyon]], where he provided the assist for [[Ousmane Dembélé]]'s opening goal and won a penalty in the second half, which was converted by [[Vitinha (footballer, born February 2000)|Vitinha]].<ref>{{cite news |date=15 December 2024 |title=PSG's Desire Doue takes a big step forward ahead of crucial Champions League and Ligue 1 battles |url=https://www.cbssports.com/soccer/news/psgs-desire-doue-takes-big-step-forward-ahead-of-crucial-champions-league-ligue-1-battles/ |access-date=17 December 2024 |website=CBS Sports}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Ligue 1 : Porté par un grand Désiré Doué, le PSG retrouve le succès en Ligue 1 dans le choc face à l'OL |url=https://www.lequipe.fr/Football/Actualites/Porte-par-un-grand-desire-doue-le-psg-retrouve-le-succes-en-ligue-1-dans-le-choc-face-a-l-ol/1526877 |access-date=19 December 2024 |publisher=L'Équipe |language=fr}}</ref> On 19 February 2025, Doué came on as a substitute in the second leg of a [[2024–25 UEFA Champions League knockout phase|Champions League knockout phase]] play-off against fellow Ligue 1 club [[Stade Brestois 29|Brest]], where he scored a goal and provided an assist in an eventual 7–0 win for PSG.<ref>{{cite web |date=19 February 2025 |title=Ruthless PSG demolish Brest 7-0 to seal last-16 spot|url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/report/_/gameId/732196| access-date=29 March 2025 |website=ESPN}}</ref>

Doué's stature in the PSG squad continued to grow with impressive performances including a game against Lille on 1 March, where he got a goal and an assist.<ref>{{cite web |date=1 March 2025 |title=Leaders PSG score four 1st-half goals to thrash Lille |url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/report/_/gameId/732196| access-date=29 March 2025 |website=ESPN}}</ref> On 11 March, in the second leg of the Champions League round of 16 tie against [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]], Doué came on as a substitute for [[Bradley Barcola]] and scored the decisive penalty at [[Anfield]] that won the Parisians the tie in a second leg comeback, after having lost the first leg 1–0.<ref>{{cite web |date=11 March 2025 |title=Doue scores penalty to knock Liverpool out.|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/videos/c89y8k037v3o| access-date=29 March 2025 |website=BBC Sport}}</ref> His performances in March, in which he scored three goals and recorded two assists in four Ligue 1 matches, saw him named [[UNFP Player of the Month]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://en.psg.fr/teams/first-team/content/desire-doue-paris-saint-germain-wins-the-unfps-ligue-1-player-of-the-month-award-for-march-2024-2025|title=Désiré Doué wins UNFP's Ligue 1 Player of the Month award for March|date=14 April 2025|access-date=2 June 2025|publisher=Paris Saint-Germain FC}}</ref> On 5 April, Doué scored the only goal in a 1–0 victory over [[Angers SCO|Angers]], securing his club's 13th Ligue 1 title.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/live/c7vn674q55lt |title=PSG 1–0 Angers SCO |publisher=BBC Sport |date=5 April 2025 }}</ref> Four days later, he scored the equalizer in the Champions League quarter-final first leg against [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]] from outside the box,<ref>{{Cite web |date=9 April 2025 |title=Doue epitomises PSG - this could be their time |url= https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/articles/crm33dzl7dlo|website=BBC Sport}}</ref> with PSG going on to win the tie 5–4 on aggregate to advance to the semi-final stage.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/athletic/live-blogs/aston-villa-vs-psg-live-updates-champions-league-score-result/be31E4IJWGee/H9kwH4sPSlW8/|title=How PSG made the Champions League semi-final despite Aston Villa's spirited second-half comeback|date=16 April 2025|access-date=2 June 2025|website=The Athletic}}</ref> He went on feature as PSG's starting right winger in both legs of the semi-final against [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] as PSG reached the second Champions League final in the club's history with a 3–1 aggregate win over the London club.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/live/clyqdmn0drgt|title=Arsenal 0-1 PSG: Ousmane Dembele's early goal gives PSG advantage in Champions League semi-final|access-date=2 June 2025|date=29 April 2025|website=BBC Sport}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/live/czjnxym0n74t|title=PSG beat Arsenal to set up Champions League final with Inter|access-date=7 May 2025|date=29 April 2025|website=BBC Sport}}</ref> At the end of the league season, he was named as both the [[Ligue 1 Young Player of the Year|Young Player of the Year]] and in the Ligue 1 Team of the Year at the [[Trophées UNFP du football|2025 UNFP awards]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ligue1.com/en/articles/l1_article_2530-unfp-desire-doue-captures-young-player-of-the-year-award|title=UNFP: Désiré Doué captures Young Player of the Year Award!|date=13 May 2025|access-date=2 June 2025|website=Ligue 1}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://ligue1.com/articles/l1_article_2529-unfp-psg-stars-lead-the-way-in-team-of-the-year-honors|title=UNFP: PSG Stars Lead the Way in Team of the Year Honors|date=13 May 2025|access-date=2 June 2025|website=Ligue 1}}</ref>

On 31 May, Doué scored twice and provided an assist to [[Achraf Hakimi]] in a 5–0 win over [[Inter Milan]] in the [[2025 UEFA Champions League final|Champions League final]], being awarded [[Player of the match|man of the match]], as his club secured their first-ever title in the competition.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/news/0299-1de41a81a0d8-2cfefc69a802-1000--desire-doue-named-official-2025-uefa-champions-league-final/ |title=Désiré Doué named official 2025 UEFA Champions League final Player of the Match |publisher=UEFA |date=31 May 2025 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |date=1 June 2025 |title='I have no words' - Champions League final MVP Desire Doue pays tribute to head coach Luis Enrique for trusting PSG star to step into Kylian Mbappe's shoes English Saudi Arabia |url=https://www.goal.com/en-sa/lists/i-have-no-words-champions-league-final-mvp-desire-doue-pays-tribute-to-head-coach-luis-enrique-for-trusting-psg-star-to-step-into-kylian-mbappe-s-shoes/blta19ecb4df34588aa |access-date=1 June 2025 |website=Goal.com}}</ref> In addition, he became the first ever teenager to score a brace in the final at the age of 19 years and 362 days, surpassing [[Eusébio]]'s record, aged 20 years and 97 days, set in 1962,<ref>{{cite web |last=McNulty |first=Phil |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/articles/cnv1g944vggo |title=New-look PSG make history on emotional night for Luis Enrique |website=BBC Sport |date=1 June 2025 }}</ref> as well as the youngest assist provider in a final, overtaking [[Jude Bellingham]]'s record (aged 20 years and 338 days) from the [[2024 UEFA Champions League final|previous season]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://theanalyst.com/articles/psg-vs-inter-stats-champions-league-final |title=PSG 5-0 Inter Stats: Doué Dazzles as PSG Record Biggest Ever Champions League Final Win |publisher=Opta Analyst |date=31 May 2025 }}</ref> He also became the second teenager to score a goal and assist in a final since [[Brian Kidd]] in 1968 and the first player with 3 goal involvements in a final since [[Sandro Mazzola]] in 1964.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://iffhs.com/posts/4400 |title=The records of Désiré Doué |website=iffhs.com |date=1 June 2025 }}</ref> Due to his impressive performances, Doué was named the [[UEFA Champions League#Young Player of the Season|UEFA Champions League Young Player of the Season]].<ref name="YPOTS"/>

On 6 June, in the [[2025 FIFA Club World Cup knockout stage#Paris Saint-Germain vs Bayern Munich|quarter-finals of the 2025 FIFA Club World Cup]], Doué scored the first goal against [[FC Bayern Munich|Bayern Munich]] to help PSG advance to the semifinals of tournament.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://sports.yahoo.com/article/jamal-musiala-suffers-fractured-fibula-180000960.html |title=Jamal Musiala suffers fractured fibula |publisher=Yahoo Sports |date=5 July 2025 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Bonn |first=Kyle |date=2025-07-05 |title=What happened to Jamal Musiala? Bayern star suffers horror leg break injury in Club World Cup quarterfinal |url=https://www.sportingnews.com/us/soccer/news/jamal-musiala-horror-injury-club-world-cup-bayern-munich/d344f5d5d43af3ce6ec0a66b |access-date=6 July 2025 |website=[[The Sporting News]] |language=en-us}}</ref> Although his team lost in the [[2025 FIFA Club World Cup final|final]] against [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]], he was awarded the Best Young Player of the tournament.<ref>{{cite web |last=Butler |first=Michael |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/live/2025/jul/13/chelsea-psg-club-world-cup-2025-final-live |title=Chelsea 3-0 Paris Saint-Germain: Club World Cup 2025 final – as it happened |publisher=The Guardian |date=14 July 2025 }}</ref>

==International career==

Doué was a youth international for France, having represented the [[France national under-17 football team|France U17]]s and [[France national under-19 football team|France U19s]]. He played for the U17s in their winning campaign at the [[2022 UEFA European Under-17 Championship]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lequipe.fr/Football/Actualites/La-france-remporte-l-euro-des-moins-de-17-ans-contre-les-pays-bas/1336386|title=La France remporte l'Euro des moins de 17 ans contre les Pays-Bas|website=L'Équipe}}</ref> and the U19s in the [[2024 UEFA European Under-19 Championship]] qualifiers. Doué debuted for the [[France national under-21 football team|France under-21 team]] on 13 October 2023 in the [[UEFA European Under-21 Championship|UEFA European under-21 championship]] qualifying match against [[Bosnia and Herzegovina national football team|Bosnia and Herzegovina]], where he picked up two yellow cards and was sent off before the final whistle.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Déchelotte |first=Arnaud |date=16 October 2023 |title=Après son carton rouge, Doué quitte le rassemblement des Espoirs |url=https://www.beinsports.com/fr-fr/football/articles/aprs-son-carton-rouge-dou-quitte-le-rassemblement-des-espoirs-2023-10-16 |website=beIN SPORTS}}</ref>

On 22 March 2024, Doué made his debut for the [[France Olympic football team]] in a friendly match against [[Cote d'ivoire national football team|Cote D'Ivoire]], scoring two goals in a 3–2 win.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Vincent |first=Roussel |date=22 March 2024 |title=MATCH AMICAL {{!}} LES BLEUETS S'EN SORTENT BIEN FACE À CÔTE D'IVOIRE : REVIVEZ LE MATCH |url=https://www.eurosport.fr/football/france-espoirs-cote-d-ivoire-espoirs-en-direct_sto10073001/story.shtml |access-date=23 March 2024 |website=eurosport.fr}}</ref> He played in five matches at the [[2024 Summer Olympics|2024 Olympic games]], including a notable appearance from the bench in the final against [[Spain Olympic football team|Spain]], which France lost 5–3, having to settle for the runner-up position in the tournament it hosted.

On 13 March 2025, Doué received his first call-up to the [[France national football team|France national team]] and made his debut in the [[2024–25 UEFA Nations League]] quarter-final against [[Croatia national football team|Croatia]].<ref>{{Cite web |date=13 March 2025 |title=Équipe de France : première convocation chez les Bleus pour Désiré Doué, un talent façonné au Stade Rennais – ici |url=https://www.francebleu.fr/sports/football/equipe-de-france-premiere-convocation-chez-les-bleus-pour-desire-doue-un-talent-faconne-au-stade-rennais-6849400 |access-date=17 March 2025 |website=ici, le média de la vie locale |language=fr}}</ref>

On 8 June 2025, Doué received the bronze medal for getting 3rd place in the [[2024-25 UEFA Nations League|2024–25 UEFA Nations League]] with France after a 2–0 victory against [[Germany national football team|Germany]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.uefa.com/uefanationsleague/news/029a-1df3af7eedc9-c3b6e51cf3f1-1000--germany-vs-france-highlights-and-report-kylian-mbappe-sco/ |title=Germany vs France highlights and report: Kylian Mbappé scores 50th goal as Les Bleus clinch Nations League third place |publisher=UEFA |date=8 June 2025 }}</ref> He played a total of 138 minutes in the tournament.

On 29 March 2026, Doué scored his first international goals in a friendly against Colombia.

== Style of play and reception ==
Considered to be one of the best young players in the world,<ref name=":0">{{Cite web |last=Swan |first=Rob |last2=Ritchie |first2=Calum |date=30 June 2022 |title=The 25 best young players in world football right now - ranked in order |url=https://www.givemesport.com/best-young-players-in-world-football-soccer-ranked/ |access-date=18 July 2025 |website=GiveMeSport |language=en}}</ref><ref name=":1">{{Cite web |date=1 June 2025 |title=Doué beats Yamal to Champions League award |url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/story/_/id/45421551/champions-league-desire-doue-pips-lamine-yamal-young-player-award |access-date=18 July 2025 |website=ESPN.com |language=en |quote=Both teenagers -- slated as perhaps the two best young players in world football -- made the team of the season.}}</ref><ref name=":2">{{Cite web |last=Kenmare |first=Jack |date=2 July 2025 |title=Man Utd fans are only just finding out who they held 'initial talks' with last summer and it could have changed everything |url=https://www.sportbible.com/football/football-news/man-utd/man-utd-transfer-news-premier-league-champions-league-902576-20250602 |access-date=18 July 2025 |website=SPORTbible |language=en}}</ref><ref name=":3">{{Cite web |last=Burns |first=Euan |date=7 May 2025 |title=Sports Illustrated |url=https://www.si.com/onsi/soccer/real-madrid/transfers-and-rumors/psg-dashes-real-madrid-s-hopes-of-signing-talented-frenchman |access-date=18 July 2025 |website=Real Madrid CF On SI |language=en-us}}</ref> Doué's natural position is an [[attacking midfielder]], but his versatility allows him to play deeper in midfield, on either wing, or as a forward, depending on the formation. A dynamic box-to-box playmaker with an eye for goal, Doué has been noted for his supreme agility, acceleration and pace, which combined with his excellent dribbling, shooting and passing technique allows him to be a potent offensive threat in a variety of situations.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Kulig |first=Jacek |date=21 December 2022 |title=Désiré Doué: The Gifted One by Vuyo Ndebele |url=https://footballtalentscout.net/2022/12/21/desire-doue-the-gifted-one-by-vuyo-ndebele/ |website=Football Talent Scout |access-date=12 November 2023 |archive-date=5 December 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231205115248/https://footballtalentscout.net/2022/12/21/desire-doue-the-gifted-one-by-vuyo-ndebele/ |url-status=dead }}</ref> According to journalist Liam Tharme, who analyzed the player for ''[[The Athletic]]'', Doué's super-strength is ball carrying, ranking inside the top two percent of central midfielders in the top five European leagues over the 2022–2023 season for progressive carries (3.4 per 90), and the top one percent for successful dribbles (3.9).<ref>{{Cite web |last=Tharme |first=Liam |date=2 August 2023 |title=Desire Doue: The latest gifted prospect from the Rennes production line |url=https://www.nytimes.com/athletic/4696681/2023/08/01/desire-doue-the-latest-gifted-prospect-from-the-rennes-production-line/ |website=The Athletic}}</ref> [[ESPN]] describes Doué as "an entertainer at heart, full of tricks and skills designed to shake up opponents".<ref>{{Cite web |date=2 July 2023 |title=Best XI: Young bargain signings in each top European league |url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/story/_/id/37943775/who-makes-our-best-xi-bargain-signings-top-european-league |website=ESPN}}</ref> Despite being primarily used as an attacking player, Doué has also been praised for his defensive contribution, demonstrated by his average of more than three tackles per game in [[Ligue 1]], which has placed him in the top six percent of midfielders in the league.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Deepak Tripathi |first=Saumy |date=26 October 2022 |title=Who is Desire Doue: The perfect successor to Eduardo Camavinga |url=https://www.foottheball.com/players-in-focus/who-is-desire-doue-stade-rennais-potential-analysis-scout-report-future/ |website=FootTheBall}}</ref>

Rennes manager Bruno Génésio has spoken highly of Doué, calling the youngster "physically already equipped" and further complimenting him: "He reads the game very well. Technically, right foot and even left foot, he's complete, with good control on both. Away from the pitch he's a dream. Easy, calm, with a streak of leadership whilst still asking for advice. He's both care-free and conscientious in his work. He's already a pro in his head".<ref>{{Cite web |date=15 September 2022 |title=One to watch: Désiré Doué, Rennes' latest prodigy |url=https://www.ligue1.com/articles/news/2022/09/15/rising-star-desire-doue |website=Ligue 1 Uber Eats}}</ref> Veteran midfielder [[Nemanja Matić]] who signed for Rennes in the summer of 2023 stated that Doué has great potential.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Telford |first=S |date=30 September 2023 |title='Désiré Doué has great potential' says Nemanja Matic |url=https://www.ligue1.com/Articles/News/2023/09/30/desire-doue-has-great-potential-says-nemanja-matic |website=Ligue 1 Uber Eats}}</ref>

Doué has also drawn comparisons to former PSG player [[Neymar]], particularly after his arrival at the French club, where he has been cited as the Brazilian's heir due to his creativity, flair, dribbling prowess and eye for goal. PSG manager Luis Enrique has praised Doué for his "technical ability, physicality, and personality".<ref>{{Cite web |last=Kovbasa |first=Ivan |title='I remember you criticised him': Luis Enrique's glowing praise for Desire Doue |url=https://tribuna.com/en/news/2025-03-15-i-remember-you-criticised-him-luis-enriques-glowing-praise-for-desire-doue/ |access-date=7 April 2025 |website=Tribuna.com|date=15 March 2025 }}</ref>

== Personal life ==
Doué was born in [[Angers]], Maine-et-Loire,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.lequipe.fr/Football/FootballFicheJoueur95612.html |title=Désiré Doué |newspaper=L'Équipe |location=Paris |access-date=16 March 2025 |language=fr}}</ref> to an Ivorian father and French mother.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.francetvinfo.fr/sports/foot/ligue-1/ligue-1-qui-est-desire-doue-le-nouveau-milieu-de-terrain-du-paris-saint-germain-arrive-de-rennes_6729729.html|title=Ligue 1 : qui est Désiré Doué, le nouveau talent français recruté par le Paris Saint-Germain ?|date=17 August 2024|website=Franceinfo}}</ref> He holds French and Ivorian citizenships.<ref>{{Cite web |date=15 April 2022 |title=Rennes : Désiré Doué signe son premier contrat professionnel |url=https://amsport.live/rennes-desire-doue-signe-son-premier-contrat-professionnel |website=AmSport |access-date=7 August 2022 |archive-date=7 August 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220807191543/https://amsport.live/rennes-desire-doue-signe-son-premier-contrat-professionnel |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.unfp.org/joueur/desire-doue-25504/ |title=Désiré Doué |publisher=unfp.org |language=fr }}</ref> His brother [[Guéla Doué]] and his cousins [[Yann Gboho]], [[Marc-Olivier Doué]], and [[Eddy Doué]] are also professional footballers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.footmercato.net/a8278659965667783859-rennes-desire-doue-signe-son-premier-contrat-professionnel|title=Rennes : Désiré Doué signe son premier contrat professionnel|first=Josué|last=Cassé|website=Foot Mercato : Info Transferts Football - Actu Foot Transfert|date=15 April 2022 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sottoporta.it/attenzione-a/attenzione-a-desire-doue/|title=Attenzione a... Désiré Doué|first=Lorenzo|last=Lombardi|date=23 October 2022}}</ref> His uncle and godfather [[Noumandiez Doué]] was a former Ivorian international referee.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Trésarrieu |first=Flavien |date=11 March 2026 |title=L'arbitre de la famille |url= |trans-title=The family referee|journal=L'Equipe |language=fr |location=France|publisher= |access-date=13 March 2026}}</ref>

Doué has recognised both [[Neymar]] and [[Lionel Messi]] as his footballing idols.<ref>{{Cite web |date=7 April 2025 |title=Rennes : The Désiré Doué Interview |url=https://onefootball.com/de/news/rennes-the-desire-doue-interview-39592237 |access-date=7 April 2025 |website=OneFootball |language=de}}</ref>

